WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.400
Hi everyone, I'm really excited to be here. So let's start. I personally believe that

00:00:12.400 --> 00:00:18.440
the future of knowledge work will eventually be remote. So in some sense, we all got to

00:00:18.440 --> 00:00:24.760
experience the future in the last few months. However, this might not have been what you

00:00:24.760 --> 00:00:29.840
hope for, because setting up a collaborative environment for your data science team can

00:00:29.840 --> 00:00:35.599
be challenging, even when working side by side in an office. At Apsilon, we spent years

00:00:35.599 --> 00:00:42.480
developing efficient systems for remote collaboration. And in this presentation, I will cover the

00:00:42.480 --> 00:00:51.639
best practices that work for us. So I'm Olga Mierzwa-Sulima, and I'm a senior data scientist

00:00:51.639 --> 00:00:57.119
and an experienced project leader at Apsilon. I have a background in econometrics, and my

00:00:57.119 --> 00:01:05.559
main technological stack at work is R. I have been building our community here in Warsaw

00:01:05.559 --> 00:01:16.639
since 2014. I plan to cover three areas in my talk. So project management, doing effective

00:01:16.639 --> 00:01:24.760
code reviews, and setting up a painless development environment in R. So when it comes to project

00:01:24.760 --> 00:01:30.519
management, almost all of the projects that we run in Apsilon are managed with Scrum approach

00:01:30.519 --> 00:01:38.199
with small variations. At the beginning of the project, we sit down together with our

00:01:38.199 --> 00:01:43.800
client and collect the requirements that are translated to high level tasks in the project

00:01:43.839 --> 00:01:50.839
backlog. At this stage, we also provide a high level estimate on how much time we think

00:01:50.839 --> 00:01:56.599
we need. For example, we contract work for eight weeks, each with one week long sprint.

00:01:57.879 --> 00:02:05.839
Every sprint starts with a sprint planning, where the dev team and the client select the

00:02:05.839 --> 00:02:13.720
tasks to work in a given week, and we also set the varieties. During the week, we meet daily

00:02:13.720 --> 00:02:21.639
inside the dev team to get each other updates. We also use those meetings as an opportunity to

00:02:21.639 --> 00:02:26.440
catch up on the small things that are happening inside the team, because we don't have those

00:02:26.440 --> 00:02:32.440
random meetings in an office that happen next to the coffee machine. The rest of the

00:02:32.440 --> 00:02:39.520
communication during the week, we try to do async using a dedicated project channel on Slack.

00:02:39.520 --> 00:02:46.520
We also use Slack to give each other updates such as that we start or finish work or are in

00:02:46.520 --> 00:02:54.759
the do not disturb mode. We also hold one on ones between team members to discuss specific

00:02:54.759 --> 00:03:04.080
problems related to the project. But coming back to our scrum process at the end of the week,

00:03:04.080 --> 00:03:11.720
we do the sprint review where we show to our client the increment. Usually this means doing a demo of a

00:03:11.720 --> 00:03:19.679
shiny app with new features or going to a notebook that validates new data science hypothesis.

00:03:19.679 --> 00:03:29.199
We also hold retrospective meetings to celebrate things that went well or to discuss potential improvements.

00:03:29.199 --> 00:03:40.039
We use project board to help us manage backlog. We usually use tools available from GitHub, Asana or Jira.

00:03:40.039 --> 00:03:46.600
So agile development is standard and common practice, but making it work for your team is a clue.

00:03:46.600 --> 00:03:55.360
So we make sure to always have a well-organized project report that is reflecting the current status of work.

00:03:55.360 --> 00:04:04.000
So basically, if I look into the project report, it should tell me who is working on what tasks and what are the varieties.

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:08.880
Also, at Absalom, we have this rule that all work needs to be documented.

00:04:08.880 --> 00:04:15.639
So whatever you are doing, there should be a corresponding task describing it on the project report.

00:04:15.639 --> 00:04:23.399
The task needs to have a clear and informative description, which is understandable not only to the dev team,

00:04:23.399 --> 00:04:28.200
but also to our clients as they have access to the project report as well.

00:04:28.200 --> 00:04:35.519
We introduced an implementation plan, which is something that is non-standard to a classical Kanban view.

00:04:35.519 --> 00:04:44.679
Basically, the person who is doing the task has to provide a description how they will approach the task and get an acceptance from another team

00:04:44.679 --> 00:04:49.160
member before starting the actual implementation.

00:04:49.160 --> 00:04:55.920
This way, we make sure that any proposed change makes sense and we verify it early enough.

00:04:55.920 --> 00:05:06.160
Finally. The reviewer is responsible to check if the solution corresponds to the task requirement.

00:05:06.160 --> 00:05:12.119
As you probably noticed, our project management flow is tightly related to code review.

00:05:12.119 --> 00:05:21.359
I will assume that majority of you are familiar with that concept and I will only talk what makes it effective.

00:05:21.359 --> 00:05:27.679
We have a checklist that is part of our definition of done for a task and includes the following points.

00:05:27.679 --> 00:05:32.480
All the code needs to be peer reviewed and there are no exceptions from this rule.

00:05:32.480 --> 00:05:38.559
So even fixing a typo in the documentation needs to be peer reviewed.

00:05:38.600 --> 00:05:47.760
We also make sure that continuous integration checks are such as linter, unit tests, integration tests are configured and passed.

00:05:47.760 --> 00:05:52.839
Next, any added or modified code has to follow our style guide.

00:05:52.839 --> 00:05:59.079
This is especially important because it allows us to ensure quality, do more effective code reviews,

00:05:59.079 --> 00:06:03.600
learn from each other and spot bugs in the code more easily.

00:06:03.600 --> 00:06:10.959
Next, all the changes needs to be tested manually or with automated tests.

00:06:10.959 --> 00:06:23.679
Further, we need to make sure that no new errors or warnings have been introduced and that readme documentation and code comments have been updated according to the change.

00:06:23.679 --> 00:06:36.040
We try to automate as many things as possible and we use continuous integration with GitHub actions to perform automatic checks and let the machines do the job.

00:06:36.040 --> 00:06:42.799
For example, we automatically run unit tests after every code push.

00:06:42.799 --> 00:06:57.279
We also use project templates to initialize the structure for typical project types and use full request templates that contains a definition of done checklists from the previous slide to help the reviewer do the review.

00:07:00.119 --> 00:07:03.279
So finally, we can talk about the development environment.

00:07:03.279 --> 00:07:11.959
It's the most crucial part when working in R, otherwise the same code can give different results on different machines.

00:07:11.959 --> 00:07:20.320
Other projects can be affected, as in a global environment, packages can change and crash unrelated projects.

00:07:20.320 --> 00:07:28.720
Deployment can give you a real headache because establishing infrastructure can be challenging if it's not being tracked.

00:07:28.720 --> 00:07:36.720
And last but not least, your team members will waste time setting up an environment rather than jumping straight to work.

00:07:36.720 --> 00:07:46.399
This might not be a problem when starting a new project, but imagine adding a new team member in the middle or at the end of the project.

00:07:46.399 --> 00:07:56.160
To solve all of those issues, we do the development in RStudio running inside a Docker container, which is fixed and dedicated per project.

00:07:56.160 --> 00:08:03.079
We leverage Docker and REND to control underlying system, system dependencies and R packages.

00:08:03.079 --> 00:08:07.880
Docker and REND package together make team collaboration easy.

00:08:07.880 --> 00:08:21.600
All the changes to a Docker file or REND log file that records packages used in the project are committed and pushed to Docker Hub or GitHub from where they can be accessed by other team members.

00:08:21.600 --> 00:08:31.279
Previous solution, however, still requires some level of DevOps skills to set up everything.

00:08:31.279 --> 00:08:47.679
So some of our clients choose RStudio server because it allows their data science team to purely focus on delivering value using their core competencies in a highly secure and flexible development environment.

00:08:47.679 --> 00:08:55.799
There is no secret recipe to make your data science team work efficiently.

00:08:55.799 --> 00:09:10.960
In fact, we found that using Scrum with well-organized project board, doing code reviews and taking care of the development environment is essential for project success, no matter how your team is structured.

00:09:10.960 --> 00:09:13.000
Thank you very much.

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:20.039
And next, my colleague Pedro will tell you how to build a dashboard that can speak for itself.

00:09:20.039 --> 00:09:29.000
When dealing with users adoption, you can always be next to them and you cannot always be next to them and explain how your app will work.

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:33.359
It's even more difficult when working remotely.

00:09:33.400 --> 00:09:45.559
So I think one very important thing when it comes to remote teams is that you're not always building dashboards for for external users.

00:09:45.559 --> 00:09:49.479
You're sometimes also building dashboards for your own teams to work in.

00:09:49.479 --> 00:10:00.200
And like Olga said, when you're in the office and you're next to someone, it's very easy to just push them in the right direction of how to use it.

00:10:00.200 --> 00:10:15.320
But if you don't have this direct contact with with your users, you end up having a good solution for this is to put a bit of extra work into your dashboards and actually make them speak by speak for themselves,

00:10:15.320 --> 00:10:18.239
especially when there's alternative dashboards.

00:10:18.239 --> 00:10:25.239
Users typically have a choice and they will usually go for the one that feels better.

00:10:25.280 --> 00:10:41.479
So small background from me, I used to work as a web developer, so I used to do pages, I used to do applications, and eventually in the last couple of years I landed in R and in Shiny.

00:10:41.479 --> 00:10:52.599
So one of the great things that I ended up learning about Shiny is that deep down there's a lot of JavaScript, a lot of CSS, a lot of HTML involved.

00:10:52.599 --> 00:11:03.000
So this actually allows you to allow them to reuse a lot of what I used as a web developer to actually work on Shiny dashboards.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:07.599
So. Why does UI actually matter?

00:11:07.599 --> 00:11:13.840
The question is, if you have a dashboard that works, why should you actually care about making it look nicer?

00:11:13.840 --> 00:11:22.919
And the truth is that UI, the way your dashboard looks and feels is very important for your users.

00:11:22.919 --> 00:11:29.159
So this is the first experience that your users are going to get using your application.

00:11:29.159 --> 00:11:46.840
And especially now that everyone is so used to the way the Internet works, the way the applications in your phones and tablets work, users expect things to behave in a specific way.

00:11:46.840 --> 00:11:52.119
It's also very important to notice that users don't usually care what's in the background.

00:11:52.119 --> 00:12:05.159
And this is valid even for some Shiny apps. If your users use the application to get a specific insight or to get some data, they don't really want to.

00:12:05.159 --> 00:12:10.200
They don't really need to know how complicated the background process is.

00:12:10.200 --> 00:12:17.919
They want to have a nice experience. They want to be quick and efficient at using it.

00:12:17.919 --> 00:12:30.559
And in general, you end up with with this this concept that if users don't feel engaged and comfortable when they use your application, they might get frustrated.

00:12:30.559 --> 00:12:36.880
They might stop using it. Maybe they'll pick a different alternative if it's possible.

00:12:36.880 --> 00:12:48.479
So instead of going over the whole UI and what you can do, I decided to give you a couple of things that you can look at a couple of.

00:12:48.479 --> 00:12:59.440
Parts of the application that you can keep in mind, either when you're using an application or you're giving feedback on or when you're actually building the application.

00:12:59.440 --> 00:13:05.919
So I picked six very important topics, very important points when it comes to UI.

00:13:05.919 --> 00:13:15.320
The first one is you should keep your interface simple means any element that isn't actually doing anything.

00:13:15.320 --> 00:13:29.000
You should probably remove it. It also means cleaning up your dashboards also means that you'll pass a very clear message of what you're trying your users to or what you want your users to achieve.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:38.200
You end up with something that is very straight to the point because all the elements there actually serve some functionality.

00:13:38.200 --> 00:13:44.080
Another important tip is to be consistent. So if you have a text input, reuse it.

00:13:44.080 --> 00:13:50.599
If you have a button, reuse it. Users kind of learn to navigate your your application.

00:13:50.599 --> 00:13:54.200
So they expect elements to have the same kind of behavior.

00:13:54.200 --> 00:13:58.080
They expect flows to work the same way.

00:13:58.080 --> 00:14:06.840
And you can kind of define patterns of how your application flows when you have very complex applications.

00:14:06.840 --> 00:14:13.039
Another thing to keep in mind is to be purposefully purposeful in your layout.

00:14:13.039 --> 00:14:21.280
And this basically means that just because all the information is there doesn't mean that it's being shown in a good way.

00:14:21.280 --> 00:14:26.520
So adding white space where there's no information is important.

00:14:26.520 --> 00:14:31.039
Using using the UI elements to actually create some kind of structure.

00:14:31.039 --> 00:14:37.559
And in the case of dashboards, this is the sidebar, the sidebar navigation, the top navigation.

00:14:37.559 --> 00:14:43.440
All of these can help you create a bit of structure when it comes to your dashboard.

00:14:43.440 --> 00:14:47.840
It also means that you can draw attention to important information.

00:14:47.840 --> 00:14:58.400
You can you can use colors, you can use the size of the elements to actually change the way that your users perceive parts of it.

00:14:58.400 --> 00:15:09.119
Other one is you a few really good things that you can manipulate when it comes to to any kind of web application.

00:15:09.119 --> 00:15:14.840
These are color, texture and typography. So work, work with these.

00:15:14.840 --> 00:15:20.840
Don't overdo it when it comes to color, when it comes to contracts, when it comes to shadows.

00:15:20.840 --> 00:15:35.000
Use them to. Kind of attract your users to specific points of the application or to make things less and less evident and less important from from from your application.

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:40.719
Remember that different fonts send different messages, so.

00:15:40.719 --> 00:15:51.880
Bold, large phones are a different message from small, very non bright phones, for example.

00:15:51.880 --> 00:16:03.960
And also remember that the size of the phones, the way the text is arranged, it really helps people go through your application and be more efficient at their work.

00:16:03.960 --> 00:16:15.840
Also, remember to provide feedback. You want your users to always know where they are, what they're doing, if the application is still doing something or not.

00:16:15.840 --> 00:16:25.880
Using messages, progress bars, anything that gives some kind of feedback, feedback of what's happening really helps reducing the frustration,

00:16:25.880 --> 00:16:32.520
especially when you have scripts that are running for very long times or you're uploading a lot of data.

00:16:32.520 --> 00:16:37.479
You don't want to think that the app just crashed or that something is wrong.

