00:26:00.560 --> 00:26:05.560
So first of all, let's look at Shiny. There are two ways that you can scale your application.

00:26:05.560 --> 00:26:11.079
The first one is vertical scaling. This is increasing the amount of users that you have for one machine.

00:26:11.079 --> 00:26:21.199
And the other part is horizontal scaling, which means adding as many machines as you want to just to make sure that the application runs for covers for as many people as you want.

00:26:21.199 --> 00:26:29.359
So one thing to know is that you should first work on vertical scaling so that your application is fast and very robust.

00:26:29.359 --> 00:26:34.959
And then you can add as many machines as you want. Otherwise, you're going to use a lot of resources.

00:26:34.959 --> 00:26:43.359
So for the first one, there are three basically key things that you can do.

00:26:43.359 --> 00:26:49.880
First one is leverage front end, which is to use JavaScript to handle fast user interactions that do not change the data.

00:26:49.880 --> 00:26:54.800
And that's so that you don't have to actually communicate with the server that often.

00:26:54.800 --> 00:27:02.239
The second part is to extract computations to handle the resource intensive operations away from the application.

00:27:02.239 --> 00:27:19.599
So that's. Excuse me, quick check. So that the server itself isn't that overloaded with the computations, and the third one is to set the right architecture that I'm going to show you as well.

00:27:19.599 --> 00:27:30.199
One thing that you should keep in mind is if you want your Shiny application to be fast and if you want it to work for many users, you should make sure that the Shiny layer is thin.

00:27:30.199 --> 00:27:36.040
This should be a communication interface between the data and the UI.

00:27:36.040 --> 00:27:43.040
So the interface. So this is really what we see when we join different companies and work with them.

00:27:43.040 --> 00:27:49.479
There is a server, there is UI, and there is plenty of communication happening between the front end and the back end.

00:27:49.479 --> 00:28:01.119
And what you should be doing to make your application fast is first, you should make sure that a lot of operations that do not need any communication with server happen on the front end.

00:28:01.119 --> 00:28:11.359
And that the server actually calls the external services to fetch the data and to filter the data there, not inside of the memory of your machine.

00:28:11.359 --> 00:28:14.800
And then you can add as many machines as you want.

00:28:14.839 --> 00:28:18.079
So let's take a look at the first one, leveraging the front end.

00:28:18.079 --> 00:28:23.079
A few very simple things that you can do to already scale your application.

00:28:23.079 --> 00:28:25.920
I'm going to go through them very briefly.

00:28:25.920 --> 00:28:30.760
First one, rendered inputs in UI and only update them in server.r.

00:28:30.760 --> 00:28:34.199
This is a very simple thing that you can already apply to your applications.

00:28:34.199 --> 00:28:41.599
Very often people create a UI output in the UI and then they put all of the rendering in the back end.

00:28:41.599 --> 00:28:48.000
This requires re-rendering the whole widget whenever the inputs, whenever the other inputs change.

00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:50.239
And this makes the application slower.

00:28:50.239 --> 00:28:57.560
What instead you can do is you can render the numeric input on the front end and only update the inputs on the server.

00:28:57.560 --> 00:29:01.400
Very simple change already gives you a lot of leverage.

00:29:01.400 --> 00:29:07.280
Second part, you can inline JavaScript code with ShinyJS package by dinatali.

00:29:07.280 --> 00:29:15.040
Very simple thing allows you to call JavaScript right from the server and you don't have to generate the whole HTML on the back end.

00:29:15.040 --> 00:29:22.160
But you can just ask JavaScript to toggle some changes in the UI without actually going back and forth.

00:29:22.160 --> 00:29:27.160
And the third one is to set all actions in JavaScript without server.r part.

00:29:27.160 --> 00:29:34.640
So when you create, for example, an action button, you can right away create an onclick hook for the JavaScript call.

00:29:34.640 --> 00:29:43.680
And what is important here is that if you have skilled people in your team and you have created a great application that is used by a lot of people

00:29:43.680 --> 00:29:54.680
and you want your team members to grow, the JavaScript is a natural next step for them to learn to make the applications robust, look better and move faster.

00:29:54.680 --> 00:29:57.359
Let's talk about extracting computations.

00:29:57.359 --> 00:30:03.160
First idea is to use a remote API and Plumber from our studio is a great package to do that.

00:30:03.199 --> 00:30:09.439
So when you think about your application, you shouldn't load the entire data set to your application.

00:30:09.439 --> 00:30:17.920
Instead, you can ask external services to filter the data for you and you just show the user the excerpt of the data that is useful.

00:30:17.920 --> 00:30:23.599
Because very often, as Pedro mentioned, you don't need to put too much information to the user.

00:30:23.599 --> 00:30:26.160
They just want to see what they need.

00:30:26.160 --> 00:30:31.719
Then you can very easily wrap data extraction logic into a simple API with Plumber.

00:30:31.719 --> 00:30:34.880
This is done just by adding special comments.

00:30:34.880 --> 00:30:37.199
There is a great documentation about it.

00:30:37.199 --> 00:30:40.479
So make sure that you check it out if you don't know Plumber.

00:30:40.479 --> 00:30:45.199
And what is really important is that you can easily deploy this with RStudio Connect.

00:30:45.199 --> 00:30:51.160
So just as you have your applications running on RStudio Connect, with a click of a button, you can also deploy API.

00:30:51.160 --> 00:30:59.959
And many applications can actually use the same API, which allows you to reuse your code across many different projects.

00:30:59.959 --> 00:31:11.079
Side note, make sure to use efficient data libraries, because very often when you have an API, you want to share some data and you very often also read it from the disk.

00:31:11.079 --> 00:31:20.439
Actually, there are many different packages for reading data and you can read a huge amount of data without affecting the memory of the system a lot.

00:31:20.439 --> 00:31:26.160
So make sure you check out those packages and check how they actually improve the app performance.

00:31:26.160 --> 00:31:34.640
Sometimes just changing the library that you use for manipulating data can unblock a lot of potential in our application.

00:31:34.640 --> 00:31:45.680
So for the extracting computations, the second part that is very often important and crucial for the applications is to start using a database.

00:31:45.680 --> 00:31:50.719
The success story usually starts with a simple application and the data is just loaded into memory.

00:31:50.760 --> 00:31:58.280
Looks fine. I have a UI, I have data and then I have a server that filters the data and shows the results to the user.

00:31:58.280 --> 00:32:05.520
Just a simple application. However, if the file is big, like, for example, one gigabyte, it's going to cause you some trouble.

00:32:05.520 --> 00:32:16.160
First, when you have just five users, RStudio Connect is going to distribute them evenly between processes and they are not going to use, for example, three gigabytes of RAM.

00:32:16.160 --> 00:32:21.439
If you have 13 users, it can get a little bit more, but the machine is going to handle it well.

00:32:21.439 --> 00:32:30.280
However, the more users use your application, the more processes you have to create and each process is going to keep the same object in the memory.

00:32:30.280 --> 00:32:43.880
So it is crucial for you to instead of putting all of the data into memory, to put it away to a database and to just use filter methods and different selections to get the data that you need.

00:32:43.880 --> 00:32:54.359
And then your machine is going to be very light, very thin, and you can have a huge amount of users using your application and the database is going to handle all of them.

00:32:54.359 --> 00:33:03.079
Also, important thing to know is that you can use dbplyr to use different filtering just as you are manipulating data with dbplyr.

00:33:03.079 --> 00:33:06.760
So let's talk about the architecture. We all know Shiny Server open source.

00:33:06.760 --> 00:33:22.719
It allows us to very quickly deploy the application. Right away after you deploy the application, you will see that RStudio Connect is a great choice to have multiple processes to have better control on how users use your application.

00:33:22.719 --> 00:33:30.160
And it also has a great functionality of being able to deploy the applications with a single click of a button.

00:33:30.160 --> 00:33:36.599
What we like to use on our site is we use Ansible to provision the whole infrastructure.

00:33:36.599 --> 00:33:43.239
So imagine you have a bare metal machine. With Ansible, you can install all of the packages that are needed for RStudio Connect.

00:33:43.239 --> 00:33:54.599
Then you can install RStudio Connect and then you can even deploy the application because you have a great package, rsconnect, which has the whole API to deploy applications from the command line.

00:33:54.599 --> 00:34:04.040
So really, I think that everyone who does the development on a high scale, on a big scale, using Ansible is a really good choice.

00:34:04.040 --> 00:34:12.159
Now, this is the architecture that you would have for your applications. You set up multiple servers and they all have to be behind the load balancer with a sticky session.

00:34:12.159 --> 00:34:18.560
And they all have to connect to the same database. They have the authentication mechanism and the shared disk.

00:34:18.560 --> 00:34:31.360
As a bonus, there is also a great option that you can use so that, for example, you can have an offline mobile application that is using endpoints that are deployed to RStudio Connect with Plumber.

00:34:31.360 --> 00:34:39.320
So this is also something that we have done successfully. So there is plenty of things that you can do, and I encourage you to try them.

00:34:39.320 --> 00:34:43.000
You may think that this is all. Of course, this is all from me.

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:52.120
But when you think about it, you know how to create the application, you know how to make it beautiful, you know how to collaborate with your team, and then you can even scale it.

00:34:52.120 --> 00:34:59.239
But now comes the big thing, because when you have such success, then you want to share this success with others.

00:34:59.239 --> 00:35:10.280
And that is why Alex is going to tell you what you can do to actually go beyond one single project and actually make this collaboration fruitful for everyone.

00:35:10.280 --> 00:35:15.520
Thank you. Awesome. Thanks, Damian.

