And so my background is before I came to our studio, I was a data scientist and a data science team lead.

00:36:04.239 --> 00:36:06.360
Now, here at our studio, I work as a solutions engineer.

00:36:06.360 --> 00:36:16.639
And what that means is that I spend my time helping teams figure out how to make the most of open source data science tools like R and Python and how to make the most of our studio professional tools.

00:36:16.639 --> 00:36:26.959
So what I'm talking about here is sort of a combination of things that I learned as a data science team lead and also some things I've seen out in the wild throughout my time here at our studio.

00:36:26.959 --> 00:36:32.560
So let's start by talking a little about like what it means to grow a data science team.

00:36:32.560 --> 00:36:35.560
And so there are really four ways I think about growing a data science team.

00:36:35.560 --> 00:36:42.239
So the first is just straight up size, right? Like the number of people on the team is one way to grow a data science team.

00:36:42.239 --> 00:36:46.439
You can also grow a data science team in terms of velocity, right? Like what is the output per person?

00:36:46.439 --> 00:36:51.919
How much are you churning out? How much work are you getting done? How many models are you creating that sort of thing?

00:36:51.919 --> 00:36:55.479
Another way you can sort of scale a data science team is in terms of reliability, right?

00:36:55.479 --> 00:36:59.280
Are you confident that the outputs that you're putting out are correct?

00:36:59.280 --> 00:37:03.719
Are you confident that they're there, what they need to be? And then, of course, sophistication.

00:37:03.719 --> 00:37:09.360
Right. And that that could mean maybe graduating to using more advanced machine learning models or things like that.

00:37:09.360 --> 00:37:14.320
Or maybe it just means, you know, going from using mostly Excel to using more code tools.

00:37:14.320 --> 00:37:19.159
That can be a really great way to sort of, you know, grow a team in particular ways.

00:37:19.159 --> 00:37:27.679
So what I'm going to spend the balance of my time talking about today is actually a tool that I think can really help with with all of these things.

00:37:27.679 --> 00:37:32.399
And that tool, of course, is the R package. So you might be like, wait, what?

00:37:32.399 --> 00:37:34.840
You're going to talk about R packages. But I want to take a little step back.

00:37:34.840 --> 00:37:39.120
So instead of talking about like the mechanics of R packages, right, like how do you write an R package?

00:37:39.120 --> 00:37:42.000
I'm not going to talk about that. There's lots of great stuff written about it.

00:37:42.000 --> 00:37:47.280
I really recommend like Hadley Wickham's book, if if you're curious, that's that's a great resource.

00:37:47.280 --> 00:37:52.639
But what I want to talk about is the R package as a tool to grow a data science team.

00:37:52.639 --> 00:37:55.959
How does the R package work for us? Not what is the R package?

00:37:55.959 --> 00:38:02.560
But let's start off just like describing for anybody who's not super familiar, like what is an R package?

00:38:02.560 --> 00:38:09.639
So our package is a way to sort of container up, package up a bunch of functions that you use commonly in R,

00:38:09.639 --> 00:38:14.320
like much like you could put a dachshund in a cardboard box and it would be nicely contained.

00:38:14.320 --> 00:38:20.479
A package is a way to contain a bunch of R functions that sort of hang together for for some reason.

00:38:20.479 --> 00:38:27.800
And so I want to talk about like two different ways to use R packages on your data science team to help it grow.

00:38:27.800 --> 00:38:31.560
And so the first way is the team wide R package.

00:38:31.560 --> 00:38:35.800
So this is when your team writes one or sometimes a few.

00:38:35.800 --> 00:38:38.239
Sometimes the team will have several, depending on what you're doing.

00:38:38.239 --> 00:38:43.320
R packages that are for specific things and they're used across the team.

00:38:43.320 --> 00:38:50.760
And so the kinds of things you might like have in those R packages, like maybe you have particular analytical functions that you use certain machine learning models.

00:38:50.760 --> 00:38:55.199
Maybe you like always weight your regression the same way or something like that.

00:38:55.199 --> 00:38:58.360
And that can go, you know, those functions can go in our package.

00:38:58.360 --> 00:39:00.600
Maybe you have certain plotting defaults you use a lot, right?

00:39:00.600 --> 00:39:04.959
Maybe you use the same templates or maybe you actually have the same types of plots you're creating a lot.

00:39:04.959 --> 00:39:09.080
And putting those those plotting functions in our package can really help.

00:39:09.080 --> 00:39:11.199
Maybe you have templates, you can put code templates in our package.

00:39:11.199 --> 00:39:15.479
You can also put our markdown templates in an R package, which I think is a really cool use of an R package, right?

00:39:15.479 --> 00:39:19.520
Like you could have a report template that is the same way that use every time, put it in a package.

00:39:19.520 --> 00:39:22.120
Now, everybody across the team has it.

00:39:22.120 --> 00:39:28.760
And then the last part of, you know, things that that are really great in team wide R packages are data accessing functions, right?

00:39:28.760 --> 00:39:38.080
Like maybe you have particular ways you use DBI, the DBI package or ODBC and and wrapping that into an R package means that like not everybody has to remember how it works.

00:39:38.080 --> 00:39:40.000
They can just use the function in the R package.

00:39:40.000 --> 00:39:41.159
And that's that's really handy.

00:39:41.159 --> 00:39:44.199
So this is what goes in the team wide R package.

00:39:44.199 --> 00:39:46.360
But as I said, like, we're not going to focus so much on the mechanics.

00:39:46.360 --> 00:39:48.760
Like, what then is this R package for?

00:39:48.760 --> 00:39:52.479
And to me, a team wide R package is really for three purposes.

00:39:52.479 --> 00:39:54.360
The first is size, right?

00:39:54.360 --> 00:39:57.840
It's for scaling your team, particularly now that we're remote.

00:39:57.840 --> 00:40:02.560
Like you can't sit next to somebody and talk them through like this is how we do an analysis.

00:40:02.560 --> 00:40:11.520
And so the documentation and the functions in an R package are a really great tool to onboard new people to your team.

00:40:11.520 --> 00:40:15.840
And our package is also a really great tool for increasing velocity on your team.

00:40:15.840 --> 00:40:19.439
You know, if you have if you have functions in there that sort of, you know, make your work much easier.

00:40:19.439 --> 00:40:24.560
And particularly if you with every product, you go back and improve that R package a little bit.

00:40:24.560 --> 00:40:31.879
That's going to make the work just, you know, every product is going to get easier and easier and easier as that R package gets developed further.

00:40:31.879 --> 00:40:36.879
And of course, sophistication. Right. If you have, say, one person on your team, it's just a really great R coder.

00:40:36.879 --> 00:40:40.280
You can take advantage of their skills across the entire team.

00:40:40.280 --> 00:40:43.199
Or if you have like one really great machine learning engineer.

00:40:43.199 --> 00:40:48.520
Right. If they if they write those those specialized machine learning functions, everybody can use them all of a sudden.

00:40:48.520 --> 00:40:53.679
So like to me, the team wide R package is really a tool for onboarding and upskilling.

00:40:53.679 --> 00:41:00.520
Like that's that's the purpose of the team wide R package. I do want to give you two keys to making this work for you, though.

00:41:00.520 --> 00:41:06.280
So the first key is that everyone contributes to the R package by having everyone on the team contribute.

00:41:06.280 --> 00:41:09.959
You get much more buy in. People are excited. Right. They're excited to use their own work.

00:41:09.959 --> 00:41:13.639
They're excited to use the team's work. And and having that team wide R package is a really,

00:41:13.639 --> 00:41:18.159
really valuable resource in that case that that will actually gets used.

00:41:18.159 --> 00:41:25.360
And the second key, which is way more important, is that your team wide R package must have a clever name using the capital letter R.

00:41:25.360 --> 00:41:30.399
This is not optional. It is required. But I will give you a hint. Blank blank.

00:41:30.399 --> 00:41:39.040
Help R is always available. So, you know, you have no excuse for not having a clever name using the capital letter R.

00:41:39.040 --> 00:41:44.080
OK, so that's the pattern of the team wide R package or R packages.

00:41:44.080 --> 00:41:51.360
Another really popular pattern is the package per project that is like every analytical project gets its own R package.

00:41:51.360 --> 00:41:55.560
And this is a really, really great pattern as well. And but to me again, right.

00:41:55.560 --> 00:42:05.040
Like the the team wide R package is about upscaling, scaling and upscaling the package per project is really about reliability.

00:42:05.040 --> 00:42:08.600
That is that it allows you to document what you're doing in a much more thorough way.

00:42:08.600 --> 00:42:14.520
And it allows you to test what you're doing in a much more thorough way when you put those functions into a package,

00:42:14.520 --> 00:42:21.159
as opposed to just sort of using them in in in your analysis and just sort of having them that way.

00:42:21.159 --> 00:42:26.280
So I do want to go through this in just in just a little more detail here, which is that, you know,

00:42:26.280 --> 00:42:32.879
so so this is how I would structure a project that I were using this like R package per project structure.

00:42:32.879 --> 00:42:37.840
And so what I would have here is I have my like top level project directory.

00:42:37.840 --> 00:42:40.199
Right. So that would be like the whole project would be encapsulated in this.

00:42:40.199 --> 00:42:44.320
Incidentally, if I'm using a Git repo, I would put it at the level of the whole project.

00:42:44.320 --> 00:42:49.360
You know, you can have sort of these subdirectories inside one Git repo.

00:42:49.360 --> 00:42:55.479
Inside that, though, I'd have these two subdirectories out of the package and the project and have those separate from each other.

00:42:55.479 --> 00:42:58.919
And I'll come back to that in a second. But they're sort of parallel to each other.

00:42:58.919 --> 00:43:02.000
Right. The package and the project get developed in parallel.

00:43:02.000 --> 00:43:08.080
And, you know, something like DevTools load all is your friend here while you're while you're working on this.

00:43:08.080 --> 00:43:11.560
And then you have your your your project functions go inside your R directory.

00:43:11.560 --> 00:43:14.360
And this is where, right, like you can put your oxygen documentation.

00:43:14.360 --> 00:43:18.439
You can actually document all of the functions you're using in your analysis.

00:43:18.439 --> 00:43:23.959
And that's that's a really great thing to be able to have that documented for when you come back to it later.

00:43:23.959 --> 00:43:29.120
And of course, then you can also use tests. Right. And being able to unit test your code is is really important.

00:43:29.159 --> 00:43:34.199
And this is actually really important beyond just sort of reliability that that you care about.

00:43:34.199 --> 00:43:38.040
So like maybe you just want to make your your products more reliable across the board.

00:43:38.040 --> 00:43:44.320
And that's that's a really great thing to do. But also, like in some places, there are requirements that everything be tested before it go to production.

00:43:44.320 --> 00:43:50.919
This is a really great way to pull some of those tests out of an interactive mode and put them somewhere that you can actually run a script.

00:43:50.919 --> 00:43:56.840
And so this is one of the really great things about the project, our package per project model.

00:43:56.840 --> 00:44:02.760
Then, of course, you have your actual, you know, whatever the actual work is of your project, then sit separately from that.

00:44:02.760 --> 00:44:06.120
Right. That's in your you know, you might have an R markdown document. You might have an app dot R.

00:44:06.120 --> 00:44:11.360
You might have some dot R files. You might have, you know, a plumber API like like dummy and talk.

00:44:11.360 --> 00:44:15.399
Right. All kinds of things can go here. But that's separate from the package.

00:44:15.399 --> 00:44:20.919
And so I want to stick on this point for a minute. If any of you are on like our studio, our stats Twitter,

00:44:20.919 --> 00:44:27.560
there's been a really great discussion the last few days of like, should each project be a package?

00:44:27.560 --> 00:44:33.760
Not like should you write the project? The package per project is should the project have a package?

00:44:33.760 --> 00:44:38.280
And I would say, yes. There's also this whole debate of should the project be a package?

00:44:38.280 --> 00:44:45.679
And my argument is no on that. I just want to be clear, because I spent like this, you know, the last eight minutes just saying packages are amazing as a tool for developing your team.

00:44:45.760 --> 00:44:52.840
But I don't think every package should be a project, mainly because you end up with a lot of weird metadata on your project that doesn't work quite right.

00:44:52.840 --> 00:44:58.879
You can end up with some sort of weird circular dependencies where the package depend on it, depend on itself to do stuff in itself.

00:44:58.879 --> 00:45:04.000
And that that's really messy. And also, you can end up in a state where your package isn't actually installable.

00:45:04.000 --> 00:45:11.879
That's not a great place to be. So I would recommend the package can can be a great tool team wide to share functions across people.

00:45:11.879 --> 00:45:15.280
It can be a great tool for increasing the reliability of an individual project.

00:45:15.280 --> 00:45:18.199
It's not meant to be a whole project, but that's not the intent of our package.

00:45:18.199 --> 00:45:22.159
And I would argue, at least, and there are others who will argue very intelligently to the contrary.

00:45:22.159 --> 00:45:27.439
But I will argue that you should not have your entire project be in our package.

00:45:27.439 --> 00:45:32.439
OK, thank you so much for tuning in. Just a couple of my high level takeaways.

00:45:32.439 --> 00:45:37.959
Our packages are a tool for scaling and skilling your remote data science team.

00:45:37.959 --> 00:45:41.760
A team wide package is a great tool for increasing size, velocity and sophistication.

00:45:41.760 --> 00:45:47.159
And a per project package is a great tool for increasing the reliability of your work.

00:45:47.159 --> 00:45:54.120
With that, I'm going to pull back up the slide from Sam and I'll hand it over to her.

00:45:54.120 --> 00:45:59.080
Close out. All right, Katie, wonderful.

