Thank you so much, Alex. And thank you so much to all of the presenters.

00:46:03.120 --> 00:46:11.239
I thought that was a really fantastic story, starting from how to build a team to the actual tools you need down to what to be successful.

00:46:11.239 --> 00:46:15.360
So let's go ahead and jump into some questions here.

00:46:15.360 --> 00:46:21.919
I've got a few plugged in. We've got the first one here saying, could you elaborate?

00:46:21.919 --> 00:46:30.080
I think this is going to be for Olga. Could you elaborate on how people technically work together using RMS, Docker and GitLab?

00:46:30.080 --> 00:46:35.239
What's the operational pipeline here to use as a best practice?

00:46:35.239 --> 00:46:45.959
So usually how we how we do the development is that we when the project starts.

00:46:45.959 --> 00:46:54.399
So at the beginning, we build a dedicated Docker container for each project.

00:46:54.399 --> 00:47:01.719
And inside the the Docker container, we we set up in our studio.

00:47:01.719 --> 00:47:15.199
So we do the development inside the Docker container and to keep track of all of the packages and their versions and make the collaboration for the users easy.

00:47:15.199 --> 00:47:22.120
We use rent package, which is a package available from our studio.

00:47:22.120 --> 00:47:28.919
And whenever there is a whenever we install a new package, we install it to rent.

00:47:28.919 --> 00:47:33.399
So the rent log file is updated.

00:47:33.399 --> 00:47:43.600
And later, when we when we finish the work, we we need to do the either we do we commit all the changes.

00:47:43.600 --> 00:47:49.360
So we commit both the the Docker container and the changes to the code.

00:47:49.360 --> 00:48:00.159
And we can either we commit them if we use GitHub and we do it to GitHub or GitLab, it doesn't really matter which.

00:48:00.159 --> 00:48:13.560
Which service you use and and the the the Docker file is the new snapshot or you can also rebuild the image.

00:48:13.560 --> 00:48:16.840
It's a push to the Docker Hub repository.

00:48:16.840 --> 00:48:26.520
So basically, this is the this is our world workflow and how to exactly set up rent with Docker.

00:48:26.520 --> 00:48:37.479
There is a vignette available from rent package that's more or less describes how to do this.

00:48:37.520 --> 00:48:39.479
Just wanted to quickly add something.

00:48:39.479 --> 00:48:47.120
Very often, we we also have a base image that already contains cached libraries that you very often use.

00:48:47.120 --> 00:48:55.600
And multiple projects can use this image as a as a base so that you don't have to install everything from scratch.

00:48:55.600 --> 00:49:00.360
So this is something that we recommend if you want to have reproducibility across your team.

00:49:00.360 --> 00:49:01.840
That's great. Thank you so much.

00:49:01.840 --> 00:49:08.919
And and in that, are you Olga, are you using RStudio desktop or RStudio server, RStudio server pro?

00:49:08.919 --> 00:49:11.479
What does your tooling look like there?

00:49:11.479 --> 00:49:26.679
Well, this really depends. So either we are using the RStudio desktop or also we can simplify this workflow as well.

00:49:26.679 --> 00:49:30.080
So get rid of the Docker.

00:49:30.080 --> 00:49:37.679
But then we are usually working with RStudio server pro.

00:49:37.679 --> 00:49:47.080
But then we still use rent to take care of the the control over the packages.

00:49:47.080 --> 00:49:59.520
But it really depends from from what actually our clients want to achieve.

00:49:59.520 --> 00:50:06.040
Let's see. That's great. Thank you. And then let's see, I'm just looking at making sure we got questions for everyone.

00:50:06.040 --> 00:50:10.560
I see here, I believe this one is for Damian.

00:50:10.600 --> 00:50:19.639
So what recommendations can you make when the dashboard requires permissions and content dependent on user viewing the dashboard?

00:50:19.639 --> 00:50:27.879
Follow up on that, is LDAP a good fit here or what other LDAP or other authentication sources might you use?

00:50:27.879 --> 00:50:34.679
So I think that we there are two ways of handling the access to the data.

00:50:34.679 --> 00:50:37.159
Like one part, of course, is authentication.

00:50:37.159 --> 00:50:40.360
So who is allowed to access the application?

00:50:40.360 --> 00:50:47.800
And with RStudio Connect, you can actually hook up to any service that you have internally in your company.

00:50:47.800 --> 00:50:51.679
Very often companies use LDAP to have the same users, the same passwords.

00:50:51.679 --> 00:50:58.159
And you can also have single sign on and all the all the other good things with RStudio Connect.

00:50:58.159 --> 00:51:06.719
When it comes to authorization, it means that you can have two users logged into the same application, but they see different parts of the app.

00:51:06.719 --> 00:51:16.239
And usually this is something that you have to implement yourself within the application by assigning roles within the app with the business context that you have.

00:51:16.239 --> 00:51:26.120
One quick thing, I'll just add to what Damian said, which is exactly right, is that one of the ways you can do that inside Connect is that you get in the session data, you get the user and the group.

00:51:26.120 --> 00:51:38.760
So that's one of the ways that you can sort of take that data in a running session and then pass it along to, you know, use it to do authorization is that you actually get that data inside the session.

00:51:38.760 --> 00:51:46.320
Exactly, that's the very good point.

00:51:46.320 --> 00:51:51.520
That's great, thank you. So now let's quickly jump to some package talk.

00:51:51.520 --> 00:52:01.399
I'm sure everyone loves that. So, Alex, what are your recommendations when functionality should be extracted from a project specific package to a team wide package?

00:52:01.399 --> 00:52:11.439
Oh, that's that's a great a great question. My my favorite reference here is David Robinson, who's a data scientist and sort of big in the in the RStats community.

00:52:11.439 --> 00:52:17.560
He has a very he repeats says and repeats, you know, if you that you should do a lot of work in public.

00:52:17.560 --> 00:52:23.199
And if you if you say something three times to somebody, you should put it in a blog post.

00:52:23.199 --> 00:52:29.760
And my my sort of corollary to that is that if you find yourself using the same function three times, you should put it in a package.

00:52:29.760 --> 00:52:39.560
So that would sort of be my recommendation. Right. It's like, you know, it's certainly if you have three projects where you're using the same function, you should probably extract that into into a package.

00:52:39.560 --> 00:52:48.479
I would say sometimes even two is worth it. But but to me, really, the flag is just like, do I want to use this package, use this function more than once or twice?

00:52:48.479 --> 00:52:53.679
Then it belongs in sort of a team wide package for the per project package kind of pattern.

00:52:53.679 --> 00:53:00.159
You don't necessarily need to reuse it. Sometimes the testing and the documentation is worth extracting it into that that package all by itself.

00:53:00.159 --> 00:53:04.840
But if you're thinking about, you know, obviously you want to keep the namespace of your package somewhat compact.

00:53:04.840 --> 00:53:13.239
And so, you know, waiting until you need it two or three times to pull it in is is often worthwhile.

00:53:13.239 --> 00:53:20.919
If I may add to this, the great tool that you can use a product is our studio package manager,

00:53:20.919 --> 00:53:27.639
which is basically a copy of Kran within your own organization that you control and you can install all of the packages there.

00:53:27.639 --> 00:53:34.760
And this allows you to share this one package, which is private to your organization, to everyone within the organization.

00:53:34.760 --> 00:53:40.840
So be sure to check it out. That's great.

00:53:40.840 --> 00:53:45.280
Thank you, Damian. So I think we've got enough time for one last question here.

00:53:45.280 --> 00:53:51.760
I think this is a question that anybody can answer. So and I'd love to hear what all different folks think about that.

00:53:51.760 --> 00:53:59.040
So what are some strategies to maintain consistency in file locations on the server for data databases?

00:53:59.040 --> 00:54:05.760
Our scripts are markdown projects and dashboards. We have issues with files everywhere, but no structure.

00:54:05.760 --> 00:54:13.679
So what are some tips that you might have on maintaining that consistency?

00:54:13.679 --> 00:54:21.439
I'll go ahead just real quick. So I think a really great solution for this is to use a project based workflow.

00:54:21.439 --> 00:54:28.120
If you look up the Tidyverse blog, Jenny Bryan has a great article on using a project based workflow.

00:54:28.120 --> 00:54:32.320
And so what this allows you to do is to sort of make projects more self-contained.

00:54:32.320 --> 00:54:40.479
I think that's a really great place to start. Obviously, there are other tools in terms of sort of like consolidating data and database access and things like that.

00:54:40.479 --> 00:54:49.040
But starting with a project based workflow, I think, is a really powerful first step to making things sort of more projects and work more self-contained.

00:54:49.040 --> 00:54:56.959
That in a package, right? A project and a package go together really nicely for keeping things self-contained.

00:54:56.959 --> 00:55:09.600
The points from my side that I would add, if you want to have a great clean code within just one application, I'd recommend learning about different designs.

00:55:09.600 --> 00:55:18.560
For example, domain driven design is a great way of structuring projects and it applies to many different languages.

00:55:18.560 --> 00:55:27.080
There is plenty of books about it and they actually give you a good overview on how you can build your functions, your files so that they are understandable to everyone.

00:55:27.080 --> 00:55:31.280
And the other suggestion is to use different external tools.

00:55:31.280 --> 00:55:38.959
So if you make sure that, for example, there is a package manager that has all of the packages available for you,

00:55:38.959 --> 00:55:49.679
there is a specified way of deploying applications that is, for example, automated, then the more you have, the more structure you provide to your developers,

00:55:49.679 --> 00:55:54.120
the easier it will be for them to find the right way to do things.

00:55:54.120 --> 00:56:01.320
So just creating, for example, a definition of done, how things are done within the organization,

00:56:01.320 --> 00:56:16.719
how you organize your work and sharing it with others can be enough to actually have a very good clean code within your different projects.

00:56:16.719 --> 00:56:27.000
What I think is also useful is to follow, so you can have a style guide for

00:56:27.159 --> 00:56:38.639
structuring your code, but nothing stops you from having a document which also describes the best practices, how to structure your project.

00:56:38.639 --> 00:56:53.320
And if you see a repetitive pattern, you can extract this pattern and create a template from which you will initialize every new project.

00:56:53.320 --> 00:57:04.399
So basically the knowledge that you accumulated in the past project can be quite easily transferred to a new project.

00:57:04.399 --> 00:57:07.639
So this is something from my side.

00:57:07.639 --> 00:57:11.639
That's great. Thank you all so much for answering these questions. Thank you.

